We recommended that Management:

Adopt strategies to intensify collections that would improve the financial viability of the fund;
Cut down and minimize expenditures to priority projects intended for the constituents of the Municipality. Strictly observe austerity measures in the government pursuant to Administrative Order No. 103 dated August 31, 2004;
Include only priority items set forth by RA No. 7160 in the preparation of the Municipal School Board Budget and limit disbursements within the approved budget.  See that claims against the fund are supported with complete documentation; and
Require the liquidation of financial assistance granted to public school officials for proper accounting to ensure that funds were used for its intended purpose.  We recommended that Management pay directly to suppliers of goods and services for the assistance needed by public schools for their school-based activities to ensure compliance with RA No. 9184 in government procurements.

We recommended that:

The Management see that the stages of the budget process are followed at all times pursuant to the pertinent provisions of RA No. 7160 and Section 4(1) of PD No. 1445, to ensure that all disbursements are covered by an appropriation ordinance or law;
The Management ensure that programs/projects/activities to be charged against the 20% Development Fund are specifically identified in the AIP to facilitate proper implementation and monitoring.  Identify, first and foremost, the programs and projects that must be prioritized for inclusion and consideration in the Annual Investment Plan.  For those which are inconsistent with the governing rules and regulations, initiate amendments to address the needs of the constituents;
The Management faithfully carry out the developmental objectives by which the 20% Development Fund has been created and ensure optimal utilization of the fund for the implementation of projects for the benefit of its constituents.  Projects under this fund should be geared towards the pursuance of development objectives that would lead to the attainment of a truly developed community;
Financial assistance to barangays be recorded in the books of accounts as receivable from the concerned barangays for proper liquidation to ensure that funds are used only for the intended purpose; and
Stop the practice of transferring cash from the 20% Development Fund to the General and Special Education Fund without clear intention of returning the amount to prevent depleting the funds for development purposes.
